WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.381 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:03.381 --> 00:00:12.075 align:middle line:90%


00:00:12.075 --> 00:00:16.070 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA GARR: Hi, I'm Lisa Garr,
host of "Gaiam Inspirations."

00:00:16.070 --> 00:00:19.730 align:middle line:84%
Live big is the motto of my
guest today, Jack Canfield.

00:00:19.730 --> 00:00:22.330 align:middle line:84%
It's helped him stay
focused and inspired

00:00:22.330 --> 00:00:25.020 align:middle line:84%
after 144 publishers
turned him down

00:00:25.020 --> 00:00:27.200 align:middle line:84%
for the "Chicken Soup
For The Soul" series,

00:00:27.200 --> 00:00:28.950 align:middle line:84%
and it was also
the driving force

00:00:28.950 --> 00:00:32.870 align:middle line:84%
behind creating the Chicken
Soup For The Soul franchise

00:00:32.870 --> 00:00:37.040 align:middle line:84%
that to date has sold over
500 million copies in print.

00:00:37.040 --> 00:00:40.640 align:middle line:84%
And it also qualifies Jack as
America's number one success

00:00:40.640 --> 00:00:43.560 align:middle line:84%
coach, which is what he talks
about in his latest book called

00:00:43.560 --> 00:00:45.700 align:middle line:84%
"The Success Principles"
that is actually

00:00:45.700 --> 00:00:48.270 align:middle line:84%
in its 10th anniversary
revision which

00:00:48.270 --> 00:00:51.100 align:middle line:84%
has a lot more wonderful,
powerful principles

00:00:51.100 --> 00:00:52.130 align:middle line:90%
for success.

00:00:52.130 --> 00:00:52.789 align:middle line:90%
Welcome.

00:00:52.789 --> 00:00:53.830 align:middle line:90%
Thank you for being here.

00:00:53.830 --> 00:00:55.788 align:middle line:84%
>>JACK CANFIELD: Thank
you for having me, Lisa.

00:00:55.788 --> 00:00:58.650 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I'm so excited to talk
with you because goal setting

00:00:58.650 --> 00:01:02.440 align:middle line:84%
for me has always been
something that I love doing,

00:01:02.440 --> 00:01:05.370 align:middle line:84%
and I set, and then
they disappear.

00:01:05.370 --> 00:01:08.884 align:middle line:84%
And then I get off
track on goal setting.

00:01:08.884 --> 00:01:11.300 align:middle line:84%
Has this ever happened to the
people that you speak about?

00:01:11.300 --> 00:01:13.179 align:middle line:84%
Because you're such
an expert at this.

00:01:13.179 --> 00:01:14.720 align:middle line:84%
>>CANFIELD: Well,
everyone approaches

00:01:14.720 --> 00:01:15.761 align:middle line:90%
goal setting differently.

00:01:15.761 --> 00:01:18.430 align:middle line:84%
I mean, for me I set
21 goals every year.

00:01:18.430 --> 00:01:20.380 align:middle line:84%
And I have seven
areas of my life,

00:01:20.380 --> 00:01:22.990 align:middle line:84%
and I set three goals
in each of those areas.

00:01:22.990 --> 00:01:26.710 align:middle line:84%
And I usually get 17 of them
that year, and the other four

00:01:26.710 --> 00:01:29.160 align:middle line:84%
will happen within the
next 18 months or so.

00:01:29.160 --> 00:01:32.390 align:middle line:84%
And I learned very early
on when I was in my 20s,

00:01:32.390 --> 00:01:33.907 align:middle line:90%
I had a guru-- not a guru.

00:01:33.907 --> 00:01:35.990 align:middle line:84%
He was a business guru,
if you would call it that.

00:01:35.990 --> 00:01:38.935 align:middle line:84%
He was worth $600
million in 1968,

00:01:38.935 --> 00:01:40.810 align:middle line:84%
which would make him a
billionaire by today's

00:01:40.810 --> 00:01:41.350 align:middle line:90%
inflationary standards.

00:01:41.350 --> 00:01:42.320 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, my gosh.

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:43.900 align:middle line:84%
>>CANFIELD: His name
was W. Clement Stone.

00:01:43.900 --> 00:01:45.900 align:middle line:84%
He was a really good
friend of Napoleon Hill who

00:01:45.900 --> 00:01:47.230 align:middle line:90%
wrote "Think And Grow Rich."

00:01:47.230 --> 00:01:50.330 align:middle line:84%
And Napoleon Hill once
said, "Of all the companies

00:01:50.330 --> 00:01:54.120 align:middle line:84%
that ever used his principles,
W. Clement Stone's company

00:01:54.120 --> 00:01:56.490 align:middle line:84%
was the one that really
exemplified it the most."

00:01:56.490 --> 00:01:59.380 align:middle line:84%
And so when I went to work for
him when I was in my early 20s,

00:01:59.380 --> 00:02:02.420 align:middle line:84%
he taught me all
these principles,

00:02:02.420 --> 00:02:03.880 align:middle line:90%
and it really changed my life.

00:02:03.880 --> 00:02:06.340 align:middle line:84%
And so I've been using these
principles of goal setting,

00:02:06.340 --> 00:02:09.810 align:middle line:84%
visualization, affirmation,
do it now, don't give up,

00:02:09.810 --> 00:02:12.400 align:middle line:84%
all these kind of principles
that today everyone

00:02:12.400 --> 00:02:15.510 align:middle line:84%
kind of knows them, but most
people don't actually do them.

00:02:15.510 --> 00:02:18.540 align:middle line:84%
And so the trick is it's
not enough to know it.

00:02:18.540 --> 00:02:20.080 align:middle line:84%
How do you keep
yourself doing it?

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:21.960 align:middle line:84%
And there's things
like mastermind groups,

00:02:21.960 --> 00:02:24.610 align:middle line:84%
accountability partners,
coaches, mentors,

00:02:24.610 --> 00:02:26.140 align:middle line:90%
that keep you on track.

00:02:26.140 --> 00:02:28.890 align:middle line:84%
The problem with most
people, like you and like me,

00:02:28.890 --> 00:02:31.115 align:middle line:84%
is we're what we might
call solo entrepreneurs.

00:02:31.115 --> 00:02:31.990 align:middle line:90%
We don't have a boss.

00:02:31.990 --> 00:02:32.590 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Solopreneurs.

00:02:32.590 --> 00:02:34.798 align:middle line:84%
>>CANFIELD: We don't have
a boss, so we're out there,

00:02:34.798 --> 00:02:37.460 align:middle line:84%
and our tendency is to
move toward the things

00:02:37.460 --> 00:02:39.970 align:middle line:84%
that are habitual, or
comfortable, or easiest,

00:02:39.970 --> 00:02:40.830 align:middle line:90%
or whatever.

00:02:40.830 --> 00:02:43.810 align:middle line:84%
And so we have to have some way
to hold ourselves accountable.

00:02:43.810 --> 00:02:47.350 align:middle line:84%
Every one of us has proven we
have areas where we're weak.

00:02:47.350 --> 00:02:50.260 align:middle line:84%
If your leg's weak, you put
a cast on it if it's broken,

00:02:50.260 --> 00:02:52.399 align:middle line:84%
and so we need casts,
psychological casts.

00:02:52.399 --> 00:02:53.065 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: support.

00:02:53.065 --> 00:02:54.940 align:middle line:84%
>>CANFIELD: Support
until we're strong enough

00:02:54.940 --> 00:02:57.450 align:middle line:84%
to support ourselves in
those areas ourselves.

00:02:57.450 --> 00:03:01.320 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: The challenge I find
is that I set this set of goals

00:03:01.320 --> 00:03:04.780 align:middle line:84%
but something else comes up
that's equally as magnificent,

00:03:04.780 --> 00:03:06.930 align:middle line:84%
and I say yes to that
which distracts me

00:03:06.930 --> 00:03:09.450 align:middle line:90%
from the original goal list.

00:03:09.450 --> 00:03:10.312 align:middle line:90%
What is that?

00:03:10.312 --> 00:03:11.520 align:middle line:90%
Is that the act of saying no?

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:14.960 align:middle line:84%
Or is it choosing more
carefully saying yes?

00:03:14.960 --> 00:03:16.770 align:middle line:84%
>>CANFIELD: There's
nothing wrong

00:03:16.770 --> 00:03:19.250 align:middle line:84%
with changing
direction midstream

00:03:19.250 --> 00:03:21.990 align:middle line:84%
if something more important or
actually better comes along.

00:03:21.990 --> 00:03:24.990 align:middle line:84%
The challenge is-- and I
doubt this is true for you,

00:03:24.990 --> 00:03:28.690 align:middle line:84%
but I think for a lot of
people the distraction

00:03:28.690 --> 00:03:31.200 align:middle line:84%
of the new thing
protects them from having

00:03:31.200 --> 00:03:33.770 align:middle line:84%
to stay with the old thing
and actually get it done.

00:03:33.770 --> 00:03:37.090 align:middle line:84%
So a lot of time it
just is an excuse to not

00:03:37.090 --> 00:03:38.920 align:middle line:84%
hold ourselves
accountable to something.

00:03:38.920 --> 00:03:42.140 align:middle line:84%
But if someone came up
to me tomorrow and said

00:03:42.140 --> 00:03:44.925 align:middle line:84%
I'll give you $10 million to do
this project that's something

00:03:44.925 --> 00:03:47.550 align:middle line:84%
I've always kind of wanted to do
but didn't have the funds for,

00:03:47.550 --> 00:03:49.800 align:middle line:84%
and I thought it was more
important than the project I

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:52.210 align:middle line:84%
was doing, I'd
probably re-vector.

00:03:52.210 --> 00:03:54.250 align:middle line:84%
But what I find from
most people who are not

00:03:54.250 --> 00:03:56.530 align:middle line:84%
achieving their goals or
constantly switching around

00:03:56.530 --> 00:03:59.990 align:middle line:84%
is that they either, one, their
goals were "should" goals.

00:03:59.990 --> 00:04:01.707 align:middle line:84%
And if you do a
goal out of should,

00:04:01.707 --> 00:04:03.540 align:middle line:84%
like I should lose
weight, I should do this,

00:04:03.540 --> 00:04:05.040 align:middle line:84%
I should spend more
time in the gym,

00:04:05.040 --> 00:04:08.800 align:middle line:84%
or whatever, then you're
not committed to it

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:10.540 align:middle line:90%
at the same level.

00:04:10.540 --> 00:04:14.370 align:middle line:84%
I have a goal to transform
education so I'm constantly

00:04:14.370 --> 00:04:15.811 align:middle line:90%
focused on that.

00:04:15.811 --> 00:04:16.560 align:middle line:90%
It's not "should."

00:04:16.560 --> 00:04:17.340 align:middle line:90%
It's "want to."

00:04:17.340 --> 00:04:19.339 align:middle line:84%
So when I have a goal of
something I want to do,

00:04:19.339 --> 00:04:21.630 align:middle line:84%
like maybe the goal next
year will be go on a safari,

00:04:21.630 --> 00:04:22.690 align:middle line:90%
I want to do that.

00:04:22.690 --> 00:04:24.230 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to make
sure it happens.

00:04:24.230 --> 00:04:26.345 align:middle line:84%
But if I have a should
goal-- I find every year

00:04:26.345 --> 00:04:27.970 align:middle line:84%
most people get to
the end of the year,

00:04:27.970 --> 00:04:30.830 align:middle line:84%
and they have like five or six
goals they set that didn't do.

00:04:30.830 --> 00:04:32.690 align:middle line:84%
The next year, they set them
again, they didn't do them.

00:04:32.690 --> 00:04:34.360 align:middle line:84%
The next year, set
them, didn't do them.

00:04:34.360 --> 00:04:38.160 align:middle line:84%
Either that's a should goal,
or they don't know how, and is

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:39.670 align:middle line:90%
they can't figure it out.

00:04:39.670 --> 00:04:42.390 align:middle line:84%
Or they've got
little subconscious,

00:04:42.390 --> 00:04:45.270 align:middle line:84%
limiting beliefs or
major fears around it.

00:04:45.270 --> 00:04:48.450 align:middle line:84%
Fear of rejection, fear of
loss, fear of looking foolish,

00:04:48.450 --> 00:04:49.870 align:middle line:90%
whatever it might be.

00:04:49.870 --> 00:04:53.840 align:middle line:84%
So then we can address the fears
and the psychological limiting

00:04:53.840 --> 00:04:55.660 align:middle line:84%
beliefs and get
those cleared up,

00:04:55.660 --> 00:04:57.760 align:middle line:84%
and then most
people move forward.

00:04:57.760 --> 00:04:59.340 align:middle line:84%
Unless again, it's something
you really don't want to do

00:04:59.340 --> 00:05:01.130 align:middle line:84%
but think you should have
done, so you put it down.

00:05:01.130 --> 00:05:03.670 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So you have to learn
that and choose carefully.

00:05:03.670 --> 00:05:06.980 align:middle line:84%
In the beginning when I talked
about those 144 publishers that

00:05:06.980 --> 00:05:12.540 align:middle line:84%
had turned you down, what kept
you going after 100, 101, 102?

00:05:12.540 --> 00:05:14.845 align:middle line:90%
I mean, most people would stop.

00:05:14.845 --> 00:05:18.150 align:middle line:84%
>>CANFIELD: Well, it'd be like
saying your kid's drowning out

00:05:18.150 --> 00:05:21.741 align:middle line:84%
at sea, what made you keep
swimming 100 yards, 144 yards,

00:05:21.741 --> 00:05:22.520 align:middle line:90%
150 yards?

00:05:22.520 --> 00:05:23.040 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Good analogy.

00:05:23.040 --> 00:05:24.415 align:middle line:84%
>>CANFIELD: You're
not there yet.

00:05:24.415 --> 00:05:27.170 align:middle line:84%
And for me, "Chicken
Soup For The Soul"

00:05:27.170 --> 00:05:28.980 align:middle line:90%
became a divine obsession.

00:05:28.980 --> 00:05:30.860 align:middle line:84%
I don't know how to
say it any other way.

00:05:30.860 --> 00:05:32.970 align:middle line:84%
It's something that
came into my mind.

00:05:32.970 --> 00:05:35.740 align:middle line:84%
It's something I became
totally obsessed with,

00:05:35.740 --> 00:05:39.090 align:middle line:84%
and I think it was because it
was meant to happen through me.

00:05:39.090 --> 00:05:42.330 align:middle line:84%
A friend of mine
now talks about-- he

00:05:42.330 --> 00:05:45.230 align:middle line:84%
wrote a book called "Success
3.0," Marc Gafni did,

00:05:45.230 --> 00:05:48.920 align:middle line:84%
and he talks about success
is allowing evolution

00:05:48.920 --> 00:05:52.040 align:middle line:84%
to occur through you, as you,
because we're the cutting

00:05:52.040 --> 00:05:54.020 align:middle line:90%
edge of consciousness evolving.

00:05:54.020 --> 00:05:56.180 align:middle line:84%
Abe each of us has
a unique expression,

00:05:56.180 --> 00:05:58.400 align:middle line:84%
something we need to
bring into the world.

00:05:58.400 --> 00:06:00.630 align:middle line:84%
And it's not about
being rich or famous,

00:06:00.630 --> 00:06:02.240 align:middle line:84%
although that might
be part of it,

00:06:02.240 --> 00:06:04.594 align:middle line:84%
but it's about maybe it's one
person has this music they

00:06:04.594 --> 00:06:05.510 align:middle line:90%
need to bring forward.

00:06:05.510 --> 00:06:07.593 align:middle line:84%
Someone else needs to
architect new buildings that

00:06:07.593 --> 00:06:09.070 align:middle line:90%
are ecologically sustainable.

00:06:09.070 --> 00:06:12.190 align:middle line:84%
Someone else needs to fix cars
or we'd all be in trouble,

00:06:12.190 --> 00:06:13.344 align:middle line:90%
and they love doing it.

00:06:13.344 --> 00:06:15.760 align:middle line:84%
So we have to do that thing
that wants to come through us,

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:18.390 align:middle line:84%
and that book wanted to
be birthed through me.

00:06:18.390 --> 00:06:21.640 align:middle line:84%
It's like once you start having
contractions, you can't stop.

00:06:21.640 --> 00:06:22.530 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's true.

00:06:22.530 --> 00:06:24.155 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, I don't want
to do this anymore!

00:06:24.155 --> 00:06:25.655 align:middle line:84%
>>CANFIELD: Ultimately
we would have

00:06:25.655 --> 00:06:26.840 align:middle line:90%
self-published if we had to.

00:06:26.840 --> 00:06:28.350 align:middle line:84%
I didn't really want
to be a publisher,

00:06:28.350 --> 00:06:30.900 align:middle line:84%
but I would have done it if I
needed to to get the book out.

00:06:30.900 --> 00:06:34.135 align:middle line:84%
Fortunately, the
145th person said yes.

00:06:34.135 --> 00:06:37.190 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Fortunately.

00:06:37.190 --> 00:06:39.920 align:middle line:84%
Speaking of evolution,
how have you

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:42.580 align:middle line:84%
or your messages
evolved since then?

00:06:42.580 --> 00:06:45.110 align:middle line:84%
This was how long ago that
you started this franchise?

00:06:45.110 --> 00:06:47.401 align:middle line:84%
>>CANFIELD: "Chicken Soup
For The Soul," the first book

00:06:47.401 --> 00:06:52.280 align:middle line:84%
came out in 1993, so
we're beyond 20 years.

00:06:52.280 --> 00:06:55.672 align:middle line:84%
And so I think my
consciousness, and my work,

00:06:55.672 --> 00:06:57.380 align:middle line:84%
and the book's, and
all that have evolved

00:06:57.380 --> 00:07:00.110 align:middle line:84%
in the sense that-- well, first
of all, I have to tell you

00:07:00.110 --> 00:07:02.480 align:middle line:84%
I no longer am
coauthoring all the books.

00:07:02.480 --> 00:07:06.580 align:middle line:84%
We sold the copyrights
and the brand and all that

00:07:06.580 --> 00:07:09.235 align:middle line:84%
to another company
about five years ago.

00:07:09.235 --> 00:07:11.360 align:middle line:84%
And what happened was-- I
don't know if you've ever

00:07:11.360 --> 00:07:12.210 align:middle line:90%
had this experience.

00:07:12.210 --> 00:07:12.760 align:middle line:90%
Most people have.

00:07:12.760 --> 00:07:14.680 align:middle line:84%
You're doing something, you
love it, and all of a sudden

00:07:14.680 --> 00:07:16.392 align:middle line:84%
it just doesn't do
it for you anymore.

00:07:16.392 --> 00:07:17.600 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Maybe you've done it.

00:07:17.600 --> 00:07:20.099 align:middle line:84%
>>CANFIELD: So I knew I
needed to back away from it,

00:07:20.099 --> 00:07:22.140 align:middle line:84%
and fortunately there was
a group in New York who

00:07:22.140 --> 00:07:23.520 align:middle line:90%
really wanted to take it over.

00:07:23.520 --> 00:07:27.720 align:middle line:84%
And they had a better business
background, Harvard Business

00:07:27.720 --> 00:07:29.710 align:middle line:84%
School and all that,
and I'm much more

00:07:29.710 --> 00:07:31.732 align:middle line:84%
psychology and
human development,

00:07:31.732 --> 00:07:33.190 align:middle line:84%
so they were able
to take the brand

00:07:33.190 --> 00:07:34.520 align:middle line:90%
to places we never could have.

00:07:34.520 --> 00:07:37.610 align:middle line:84%
And it's been very good for
the whole Chicken Soup world.

00:07:37.610 --> 00:07:38.911 align:middle line:90%
It's all over the world now.

00:07:38.911 --> 00:07:40.660 align:middle line:84%
We actually have a
franchise, Chicken Soup

00:07:40.660 --> 00:07:41.920 align:middle line:90%
for The Indian Soul, in India.

00:07:41.920 --> 00:07:43.544 align:middle line:84%
There's about 20
books in that series

00:07:43.544 --> 00:07:45.210 align:middle line:84%
that most people in
America never heard.

00:07:45.210 --> 00:07:46.521 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow, right?

00:07:46.521 --> 00:07:47.770 align:middle line:90%
>>CANFIELD: So it's taken off.

00:07:47.770 --> 00:07:50.500 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It created a legacy
is really what you've done,

00:07:50.500 --> 00:07:54.291 align:middle line:84%
and so you've now moved
on into a different arena?

00:07:54.291 --> 00:07:56.790 align:middle line:84%
>>CANFIELD: Well, what happened
when I left the Chicken Soup

00:07:56.790 --> 00:07:58.530 align:middle line:84%
thing was I had to
recreate myself,

00:07:58.530 --> 00:08:02.080 align:middle line:84%
and so everyone said you sold
almost half a billion books.

00:08:02.080 --> 00:08:02.951 align:middle line:90%
How'd you do that?

00:08:02.951 --> 00:08:04.450 align:middle line:84%
And everyone was
going, well, I want

00:08:04.450 --> 00:08:06.040 align:middle line:90%
to be as successful as you.

00:08:06.040 --> 00:08:07.760 align:middle line:90%
You seem like it's easy for you.

00:08:07.760 --> 00:08:09.790 align:middle line:84%
And so I said, OK, I'm
going to take everything

00:08:09.790 --> 00:08:12.410 align:middle line:84%
I know about success, and I'm
going to put it in one book.

00:08:12.410 --> 00:08:13.880 align:middle line:90%
And I sat in bed one morning.

00:08:13.880 --> 00:08:17.270 align:middle line:84%
I had 114 principles,
and my publisher said,

00:08:17.270 --> 00:08:18.140 align:middle line:90%
are you kidding me?

00:08:18.140 --> 00:08:20.110 align:middle line:84%
No one's going to
read 114 principles,

00:08:20.110 --> 00:08:22.240 align:middle line:90%
so you got to narrow it down.

00:08:22.240 --> 00:08:24.393 align:middle line:90%
So we got it down to 64.

00:08:24.393 --> 00:08:27.150 align:middle line:84%
But these principles--
and I interviewed

